He seems to lay stress on the fact of his visit being accidentally at such a time, lest it should be supposed that he courted an ovation. Puteoli (hod. Fozzuoli) was a famous seaport-town of Campania on the east side of the sinus Baianus. It was founded by the Greeks of Cumae ΚΟ. 521 under the name of Dicaearchia, and the name was changed to Puteoli because of its many ‘wells' (putei) in the second Punic XVar, when it was fortified by the Romans. A colony was established there in Β. C. 194, and, being the first really good port on the south of Rome, it became one of the most considerable emporiums of foreign trade in Italy (Strabo, XVII p. 793), and also, like Baiae and its neighbourhood, a favourite resort of the Roman nobility. Cicero himself had a villa between it and the lake Avernus, which he called his Academia, other- wise Puteolanum.
